> Pre-populate with decisions explicitly stated in the source spec. Do not invent decisions to look complete — the value of this log is that every entry was actually decided.

## How to add or change

Add a new row with the next sequential ID, a one-line decision, and a real Source. Keep IDs stable so `progression.md` log entries that reference them keep resolving.

When a decision is overridden, replace its row in place with the new decision, and extend its Source with a one-line `— supersedes earlier choice; <reason>; <link>` pointing to the durable record of the change (the commit or PR, or a CHANGELOG entry if it's user-visible). Don't keep dead rows — git holds the history.

Every add or change should also generate a one-line entry in [`progression.md`](./progression.md) so anyone scanning recent activity sees it happened.

## What belongs here

- Product-level commitments — what the product is, what it isn't, who it's for, what platform/surface
- Workflow decisions that affect the whole project — where artifacts live, who reviews what, what gates exist before something ships
- Constraints the project chooses to accept — non-functional commitments like "offline-first", "single language at launch", "no paid features at v1"
- Rejection of alternatives, when the rejection is load-bearing — "considered X, chose not to because Y" can be a row if future contributors might re-debate it

## What does NOT belong here

- Implementation details — language choice, framework choice, library choice, infrastructure choice. These are dev-layer concerns and live elsewhere.
- Decisions local to a single phase — those stay inside that phase's plan.
- Reversible micro-decisions made and unmade in a session — log churn dilutes signal.
- Things the spec already settled but this project never explicitly accepted or refined — the spec is the source of truth for those.

## Format conventions

- IDs are stable anchors. When you override a decision, reuse its ID in place; don't accumulate dead rows or renumber the rest.
- Source pointers are real — section numbers, doc names, dated chats, links. Never blank, never "TBD". A row without a source has no value.
- Decision text is short and present-tense. Long context goes in linked docs; this table is for scanning.
